title: For Trade:  Mississippians' Second Amendment Rights
postcontent:
I cannot believe that Senator Wicker voted to approve debate on legislation that would establish a Federal law that effectively infringes on the right of law abiding citizens to transfer their property rights in a weapon to another individual. 

The 2nd Amendment was written to restrict "federal" infringement with respect to gun ownership. Requiring a background check is in itself an infringement as that check determines the eligibility of ownership, limits the owner's rights, compels the owner to act as a policing power, and creates an additional danger of confrontation for the transferor. 

Currently, the federal government requires background checks on the purchase of a new weapon from an FFL because that restriction is tied to the Federal government's power to license the FFL and through the federal government's dominating the area of interstate commerce. As part of getting the license, the dealer has to do the checks, and they are equipped to perform them as part of a business model. This has never been the case with private transfers with regard to federal law. There are states that require regulated private transfers, and those systems work for those States, AND that is exactly what the 2nd Amendment is designed to protect--the People's rights, as States, to regulate those transfers. 

Here Senator Wicker has "negotiated" Mississippians' 2nd Amendment rights to participate in the political process as a State, sovereign under the Constitution, to regulate the private transfers of a particular type of personal property. Until now, we have long enjoyed our rights to our property, free of taking by the government. We too enjoy the Constitutional protections of privacy in our papers, our writings and our homes. We enjoy free speech, and we are thankful that the Constitution has, thus far, prevented the federal government from infringing on the free exercise of faith and religion, all guaranteed under the First and Fourth Amendments. 

The law under debate, if passed and surviving Constitutional scrutiny, will allow the federal government to dominate where the Bill of Rights wholly intended to exclude it. The law places the first "inch of infringement" on an established guaranty in the Bill of Rights. Let's ask ourselves how long will we will continue to support politicians that are willing to negotiate those rights? If the inch is firmly established, there is no need even worrying about the mile; it will be just a given. 

I am left to wonder which other right will be up for infringement next--speech, privacy, religion, or perhaps racial equality? I thought they were well settled long ago too.  I have to wonder if I am ready to let them be negotiated also? 

I would offer that our founding fathers thought so much of the freedom of speech, the freedom of the exchange of information through the press, the freedom of the exchange of personal beliefs of faith through worship and the practice of religion, and the freedom to assemble and be heard by those that would govern us through the right of grievance, that they made them First among the many rights guaranteed under the Bill. They thought enough of the absolute necessity of these rights that they would pass the Second Amendment in order to insure their enduring effect. Is not the price of failing to protect the Second Amendment, the sacrifice of the assurances of the First? I urge readers to consider this question before casting another vote for Mr. Wicker again.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1944 Lee Enfield No4 MKI T Sniper Rifle w/Transit Chest & Scope Case
postcontent: The Enfield No4T sniper rifles were issued to British commando squads or SAS "seek and strike" units that hunted and assassinated Nazi war criminals that killed British secret agents, under direct order of Winston Churchill. These were the most effective sniper rifles of WWII due to the painstaking attention that the world-famous Holland and Holland gunsmiths put into these rifles which often shot sub MOA. They would receive only the most accurate rifles from the arms factory and then rebuild them with bedded barrels and many other refinements as well as a high quality No32 scope ( which this rifle is missing) and a transit chest to protect this precision rifle. This was in stark contrast to many countries which often used rack grade rifles with modest quality optics. The professional appraisal on the gun, transit chest and scope case was $4500. The condition was graded at a strong 90%+. A reproduction No32 scope and mount from Numerich at a cost of $750 would increase the value to $6000. With the original scope and mount the appraiser said they would put it in their store for $8000-$9000. Since I'm in it below market value I would consider cash/trade offers of around $2000. In 10 years this package will at least double in value as it sits, or more with the addition of a scope and mount. Would love to keep it but my wife wants the cash back I used to buy it :) Make me an offer. You can then contact Mr. Skennerton as the foremost authority on these rifles and author of "The British Sniper" published in 1983 for all the provenance info associated with this particular rifle assessable from the serial number. Thank you for looking.

title: For Sale:  LNIB Glock 30 with factory adj. sights. VERY accurate!
postcontent:
I specially ordered adjustable sights on this Glock 30 and waited almost a month for it to come in. I shot a friend's G30 and was deadly accurate with it, but his sights were low and it drove me crazy. The Gen 1 Glock adjustable sights were worse than horrible. They were plastic and hung off the back of the pistol! This was right when they changed to quality iron sights that came with a little tiny screwdriver to adjust the sights. The way they are adjusted now, I put 10 rounds within a 2" circle (from a Ransom rest) at 25 yards!! Unbelievable accuracy, especially from a 'sub-compact' .45ACP pistol.

I've never carried the pistol, so it shows basically no wear. What you see in the one picture on the rear groves is dust inside the valleys of the gripping points for racking the slide. I didn't notice until after I'd taken the pics and put it away. Otherwise, it's pretty well like new with the 2 factory "commercial" (don't really know what that means) 10 round mags and the sight adjustment tool in the original box that even says "ADJ" for sights on the box label. I'm pretty well thinking that with this Glock being rather unique with the factory adjustable sights on it and it being unbelievably accurate, that I'd want to get $525 out of it in cash or trade for a similar value pistol.

I'd trade for a compact (not sub-compact; already have those) Beretta PX4 Storm, FNS in either .40 or .45 (already have one in 9mm) or an XDS in 45.

postcontent: Up for sale are FIVE new, still in the original packaging Lancer Advanced Warfighter AR-15 30-round Magazines. The L5AWM is the only HYBRID AR magazine available today, featuring the best characteristics of Polymer and Steel magazine designs. The L5AWM fills the gap between the current metal and polymer magazine designs combing the best features from both designs into a unique hybrid magazine. L5AWM has the reliability of a steel magazine, the durability of a polymer magazine and the weight of an aluminum magazine. Unique to the AWM is the one piece wrap around hardened steel feed lip assembly that is permanently attached to an impact resistant polymer body. The hardened steel feed lips won’t bend, break or deform due to rough handling or long term storage. An aggressive surface texture has been applied to the polymer body to improve gripping and retrieval from pouches. The combination of steel and polymer result in a lightweight, robust magazine tough enough for professional use. The internal geometry of the Advanced Warfighter Magazine is a constant curve that has been maximized to feed the 5.56X45mm NATO round and has a non-tilting follower for trouble-free feeding. The feed lips are made from a single piece of precision formed steel that is hardened, then PTFE coated for corrosion resistance. The body and component materials are corrosion and chemical resistant, passing military chemical testing, including exposure to DEET. The L5 AWM is compatible with modern weapon systems; M4/M16/AR, HK416, SCAR16, and the ARX160 to name a few. The unique LWRCI™ Rapid Engagement Precision Rifle (R.E.P.R.) is a full spectrum weapon system designed to put devastating 7.62mm NATO rounds on target in a variety of roles. title: For Sale:  CNC Milled 80% lower AR reciever
postcontent:
These are some beautiful lower receivers, 80% complete to military specifications.  These are NOT considered receivers yet by the ATF and are not serialized - meaning there's absolutely no tracking of these units and even if purchased through a gun shop, no background check is required and no paperwork filled out. 

These are completely legal to own and complete into working receivers - 
however, as will all things gun related, know the local, state, and federal laws that apply to your particular location and circumstances.  You are responsible for You!

 All that is needed is a drill or drill press, some end mill bits (basically drill bits with flat ends) , and the jig; here's a few links to places selling the jigs:
http://ar15jigs.com/drilljigs.html
http://www.cncguns.com/tooling.html
http://www.apex-brass.com/ut-arms-drill-jig-fixture.html

Of all the places selling the jigs (and there are many more), I highly recommend CNCguns.  Those guys have been there, done it (right) and now offer the proper pieces of equipment, videos, and first hand experience.  Plus, their just plain nice guys and will take time out of their day to get on the phone and talk you through any problems.

I ordered 5 of these when all h*ll broke loose earlier this year and I'll end up building out 3, that leaves 2 to sell.  

Again, these are mill aluminum works of art that you can build into flawless operating guns that you'll be proud to own.

I am able to accept payment via CC through Google Checkout (add 3.5%) and will only charge actual shipping (no "handling" fee), and these do not have to go through an FFL - they ship straight to your door.
